"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731888","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Red Tape Challenge programme ran until 2015 and identified over 3,000 regulations to improve and reform. We are currently considering how best to continue to deliver our commitment to regulate more efficiently and effectively over the course of this parliament.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-06-28T12:55:27.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731888/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731888/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731888/answer","Stourbridge","Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731888/answer/previousversion/343","Biography information for Margot James","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-22","Business: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether it is his policy to continue with the Red Tape Challenge; and if he will provide an update of its work to date.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","856"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731889","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-13","<p>No central assessment has been carried out. The costs will vary widely based on the size and age of buildings. Local authorities may have commissioned separate assessments into the costs involved following the Government’s request in 2013 to social housing providers that they consider installing sprinklers into older residential tower blocks.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-13T15:42:51.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731889/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731889/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731889/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731889/answer/previousversion/397","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Housing: Fire Extinguishers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether his Department has made an estimate of the cost of installing sprinkler systems in (a) new build domestic homes, (b) retrofitted domestic homes, (c) new tower blocks and (d) retrofitted tower blocks.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","845"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731890","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-14","<p>No survivors of the fire have been declared intentionally homeless and none will be if they do not accept an offer of temporary accommodation.</p><p> </p><p>As the Secretary of State said on 3 July, we are committed to ensuring that families have a choice, and their wishes and needs are fully taken into account. This statement can be found at <a href="http://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2017-07-03/debates/AC706A82-B504-4E3B-9797-85F6B2F20295/GrenfellTower" target="_blank">http://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/2017-07-03/debates/AC706A82-B504-4E3B-9797-85F6B2F20295/GrenfellTower</a></p><p> </p><p /><p />","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-14T10:27:27.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731890/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731890/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731890/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Grenfell Tower: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what information his Department holds on whether any survivors of the Grennfell Tower fire who have been made statutory homeless have been declared intentionally homeless by the Royal Borough of Kensington and Chelsea Council.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731891","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government is committed to creating an environment that supports business, by striking the right balance between effective corporate transparency and the ease of doing business. Consistent with this, Companies House focuses on improving the quality of data on the register through post-registration investigation and enforcement rather than the introduction of identification requirements.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-06-29T14:52:12.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731891/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731891/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731891/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-22","Companies: Registration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to strengthen identification requirements, including proof of address, for businesses registering with Companies House.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731892","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>Information on offences separately identified as domestic abuse cannot be separated out from other forms of assault or abuse in records held centrally by the Ministry of Justice. This is because data on the relationship between the victim and defendant is held on individual court records and therefore the information requested could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","607","2017-06-30T13:28:36.017Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731892/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731892/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731892/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-22","Domestic Abuse: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of convictions flagged as domestic abuse offences resulted in a (i) custodial sentence and (ii) fine in each month since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731893","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>Personal tax credits are not taxable. All those benefiting from tax credits awards in each of the years requested will have been exempt from income tax on these payments.</p><p> </p><p>Personal tax credit statistics data for 2014-15 and 2015-16 is available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-tax-credits-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/personal-tax-credits-statistics</a></p><p> </p><p>Finalised statistics for 2016-17 will be published in due course.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-27T15:17:38.563Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731893/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731893/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731893/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received income tax exemption for personal tax credits in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","639"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731894","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-28","<p>The number of offenders sentenced at all courts for offences of engaging in controlling or coercive behaviour in an intimate or family relationship, by month, in England and Wales, from December 2015 to December 2016 can be viewed in the table which is a further breakdown of published data.</p><p> </p><p>Court proceedings data for 2017 are planned for publication on 17 May 2018.</p><p> </p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2017-06-28T15:21:34.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731894/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731894/answer","PQ 606 table.xls","Offenders Sentenced at all Courts - 2015 - 2016","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731894/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-22","Domestic Abuse: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what sentences resulted for all convictions for the offence of coercive and controlling behaviour in each month since December 2015.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731895","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>It is estimated that around 740,000 people received income tax relief for donations to charity for tax year 2014-15. It is projected that 764,000 and 784,000 people will receive income tax relief for donations to charities for tax years 2015-16 and 2016-17 respectively.</p><p> </p><p>These estimates are based on the 2014-15 Survey of Personal Incomes, and projected to 2015-16 and 2016-17 using economic assumptions consistent with the Office for Budget Responsibility’s March 2017 economic and fiscal outlook.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-27T15:19:04.61Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731895/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731895/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731895/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Tax Allowances: Charities","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received income tax exemption for the income of charities in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731896","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>The most recent complete dataset for self-assessment UK property tax returns (SA105) is for 2014/15. That dataset shows that there were 800,000 returns that contained claims for wear and tear allowance.</p><p> </p><p>This allowance can also be claimed by partnerships and individuals who complete short tax returns. However, in those instances claims for wear and tear are grouped and claimed together with other allowable expenses. Therefore it is not possible to identify the number of partnership and short tax returns that contain wear and tear relief claims.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-27T15:21:27.64Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731896/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731896/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731896/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Tax Allowances: Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received income tax relief for wear and tear allowance in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731897","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>Information on offences separately identified as domestic abuse cannot be separated out from other forms of assault or abuse in records held centrally by the Ministry of Justice. This is because data on the relationship between the victim and defendant is held on individual court records and therefore the information requested could only be provided at disproportionate costs.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah","605","2017-06-30T13:28:36.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731897/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731897/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731897/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-22","Domestic Abuse: Convictions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of convictions flagged as domestic abuse offences resulted in (i) a suspended sentence and (ii) a community sentence in each month since 2015.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731898","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>Reliefs to support the film production sector are not granted to individual investors, but to film production companies. Film production companies can claim the relief only for the production of individual films.</p><p>HM Revenue and Customs publishes official statistics on the number of films claiming and receiving the Film Tax Relief on an annual basis. The statistics are available at:</p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/creative-industries-statistics-july-2016</p><p>The most recent update was published in July 2016 and includes figures up to 2015-16. The number of films which claimed the Film Tax Relief was 255 in 2014-15 and 210 (a provisional number subject to revision) in 2015-16.</p><p>Figures for 2016-17 will be published in due course.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-27T15:25:00.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731898/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731898/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731898/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Tax Allowances: Film","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many people received film tax relief in (a) 2014-15, (b) 2015-16 and (c) 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Peter Dowd","Bootle","Peter Dowd","642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731899","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>The provisions of Part 4 of the Policing and Crime Act 2017 allow the police to impose pre-charge bail, with appropriate conditions to protect victims and witnesses, in any case where they are satisfied that doing so is both necessary and proportionate.</p><p> </p><p>This was made clear in the learning material produced by the College of Policing. As such, the reforms to pre-charge bail should not affect the police’s response to incidents of domestic abuse or to subsequent investigations and we are working with the police to ensure that is the case.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-26T16:01:13.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731899/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731899/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731899/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-22","Domestic Abuse: Bail","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the effect of pre-charge bail reforms on the police's response to domestic abuse incidents.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731900","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Government is committed to making sure that legal aid is available to those who need it most, and for the high priority cases that require it such as those detained under mental health legislation, or parents who are facing their children being taken into care.</p><p> </p><p>Legal aid remains available for appeals or applications for leave to appeal to the Upper Tribunal, subject to the applicant meeting the statutory tests of means and merits. Funding may also be available under the exceptional case funding scheme, where it is required by law.</p><p> </p><p>The Government’s reform programme will modernise the courts and tribunal system, improving the experience of everyone who comes into contact with it. We will make sure that the provision of legal support reflects the new way that the justice system works.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:24:11.637Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731900/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731900/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731900/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-22","Personal Independence Payment: Legal Aid Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if he will ensure that people who lose access to benefits as a result of a PIP reassessment are eligible for legal aid for expenses for any appeal against that decision.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","611"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731901","Cabinet Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>This Government is committed to creating a secure and clear democracy that works for all. We published our response to the Rt. Hon. Sir Eric Pickles’ report on electoral fraud in December 2016 setting out the Government’s approach to tackling the recommendations Sir Eric made.</p><p>The Electoral Commission publishes annual analysis of electoral fraud on their website. (http://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/find-information-by-subject/electoral-fraud/data-and-analysis?)</p><p>Further information on electoral fraud is available in the reports.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-27T12:35:00.473Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731901/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731901/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731901/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-22","Absent Voting: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many prosecutions there have been for electoral fraud relating to postal votes in each of the last five years; and to which parliamentary constituencies such prosecutions related.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731902","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-03","<p>All homes should be of a reasonable standard and all tenants should have a safe place to live. Under the Landlord and Tennant Act 1985, landlords have a general obligation to ensure that they keep in repair the structure and exterior of any property they rent out. Local authorities have strong and effective powers to deal with poor quality unsafe accommodation and we expect them to use those powers. Under the Housing Health and Safety Rating System, local authorities can issue an Improvement Notice or a Hazard Awareness Notice if they find a defect in the property. In extreme circumstances, the local authority may decide to make repairs themselves, or to prohibit that property from being rented out.</p><p>The Regulatory Reform (Fire Safety) Order 2005 places a duty on housing providers to undertake a fire risk assessment of the common parts of their properties and to put in place and maintain adequate fire precautions to manage the risk that lives could be lost in a fire. The Order is enforced by fire and rescue authorities.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-07-03T16:03:30.29Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731902/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731902/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731902/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Private Rented Housing: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what steps his Department is taking to ensure that recommended fire safety standards are met in private sector housing.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731903","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government would like to open more maths schools and will allocate capital and revenue funding as necessary. These new schools will build on the success of <br>King’s College London Mathematics School and Exeter Mathematics School, both of which are rated outstanding by Ofsted and were well above average for post 16 progress in 2016.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:50:11.14Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731903/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731903/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731903/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Mathematics","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much additional (a) capital and (b) revenue funding her Department plans to allocate for opening a specialist maths school in every major city in England.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731904","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>We want all pupils to benefit from a knowledge rich education. We will provide further details about the curriculum fund in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","469","2017-06-27T16:58:46.063Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731904/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731904/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731904/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Curriculum: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much funding her Department plans to allocate to the curriculum fund in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","658"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731905","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>Revenue funding for delivering the free early years entitlements is allocated to local authorities, who are then responsible for distributing it to early years providers including primary schools with nursery classes. The Government will be investing an additional £1 billion per year by 2019-20 in the free entitlements.</p><p> </p><p>The initial funding allocations for 2017-18 can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/dedicated-schools-grant-dsg-2017-to-2018</a> and funding allocations for future years will be announced in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:26:35.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731905/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731905/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731905/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much additional revenue funding her Department plans to make available for primary schools for new nursery staff in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","659"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731906","Department of Health","false","2017-06-26","<p>We are committed to offering Youth Mental Health First Aid training to a teacher in every secondary school by 2019 and to reach 1,000 schools by the end of 2017. The Government’s manifesto includes a commitment to offer this training to all schools, including primary schools.</p><p> </p><p>We have made £200,000 available in 2017/18 to train the first 1,000 teachers in 2017 and we will work with Mental Health First Aid England to agree funding for future years.</p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price","500","2017-06-26T13:19:07.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731906/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731906/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731906/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-06-22","Teachers: First Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what funding his Department plans to make available for mental health first aid training for all school teachers by the end of the Parliament in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731907","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-29","<p>Over 2,100 communities have started the process of creating or have created a neighbourhood plan since 2012. The Neighbourhood Planning Act 2017 will further strengthen neighbourhood planning, including reforms to make the process for neighbourhood planning groups to modify ‘made’ neighbourhood plans or orders proportionate to the changes proposed.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-06-29T17:31:30.337Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731907/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731907/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731907/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Neighbourhood Development Plans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to reform the way in which Neighbourhood Plans can be amended by (a) parish councils and (b) other sponsoring community groups; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for James Cartlidge","South Suffolk","James Cartlidge","692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731908","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>We are reflecting on our programmes in relation to school meals and will come forward with proposals in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:08:29.933Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731908/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731908/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731908/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate her Department has made of the resources needed to provide a free breakfast to every primary school child in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","666"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731909","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>The Government wants to test ambitious new approaches to career learning, as announced at the Budget. Detailed proposals for implementing a national retraining scheme will be set out in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","672","2017-07-03T15:08:05.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731909/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731909/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731909/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she has made an assessment of the further education provision that will be required to deliver a national retraining scheme.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731910","Department for Education","false","2017-07-04","<p>Good mental health is a priority for the Department. Mental health issues can have a profound impact on the whole of a child’s life, including their attainment. Schools can play an important role in promoting mental wellbeing and supporting pupils, but teachers are not mental health professionals and knowledge and practice in the mental health field is constantly developing. Action taken by them is best supported by advice from specialist services, as well as by access to treatment for pupils where needed. We are investing an additional £1.4 billion in children’s mental health services in the five years to 2020.</p><p>Our schools/Child and Adolescent Mental Health Services (CAMHS) link joint training pilot, across 225 schools in 27 Clinical Commissioning Groups, identified a range of different models for schools working more closely with single points of contact in specialist mental health services – making use of the additional investment. These resulted in a strengthening of communication and joint working arrangements between schools and specialist services, with quantifiable improvements in understanding of the referral routes amongst school staff – leading in many cases to higher quality and more timely referrals.</p><p>We will be considering with the Department of Health how best to build on the results of this pilot to improve links between schools, colleges and NHS mental health services as a part of our joint children and young people’s mental health green paper, to be published by the end of the year. We will look at any funding requirements in that context.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","501","2017-07-04T16:45:34.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731910/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731910/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731910/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what additional funding her Department plans to make available to ensure that all schools have a single point of contact for mental health services in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","661"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731911","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>In study programmes for 16 and 17 year old students there is a requirement for a minimum of 540 planned hours per year for a programme to qualify as full time. However, the expectation on providers is to deliver programmes of 600 hours per year and the funding rate is set on that basis. The Department for Education plans to make additional funding available to support the introduction of new technical education routes, T levels. In the March budget we announced that we anticipate the number of programme hours for students on those routes will increase to over 900 a year on average, including the completion of a high quality work placement. We are currently working through the detail of our proposals for implementing the technical education reforms and the actual amounts that will be made available are still to be determined, but will be from the additional resources announced in the March Budget for 16-19 technical education to implement the Sainsbury reforms: the first line in Table 2.1 in the Budget report. See <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spring-budget-2017-documents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spring-budget-2017-documents</a>.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","484","2017-07-03T14:41:16.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731911/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731911/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731911/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Teachers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what additional funding her Department will make available to increase the number of teaching hours to an average of 900 hours a year in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","667"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731912","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>The digital skills entitlement will ensure that adults who lack core digital skills can access specified basic digital skills training free of charge where it is made available as part of the publicly funded adult education offer. We will set out the plans to support the implementation of this entitlement in due course.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><ul><li><p> </p></li></ul>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-03T14:25:22.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731912/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731912/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731912/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Digital Technology: Lifelong Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps she plans to take to deliver lifelong learning in digital skills.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731913","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>My department will provide further information on the consultation in due course.</p>","Putney","Justine Greening",,"2017-06-27T12:52:54.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731913/answer","Biography information for Justine Greening","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731913/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731913/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to publish the results of the Schools that work for everyone consultation.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731914","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>We know that high-quality childcare is important not just for working parents but also for a child’s development and school readiness. We will provide more details on our plans in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:26:20.157Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731914/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731914/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731914/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Primary Education: Nurseries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether it is her Department's policy that all primary schools will include a nursery.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731915","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>We received over 25,000 responses to the consultation, which we are analysing in detail. We are grateful to all those who expressed their views on school funding and the proposed formula as part of this process. We will publish the response to the consultation in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-27T12:50:34.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731915/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731915/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731915/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to publish the Government's response to the second stage of the consultation on the schools national funding formula.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","663"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731916","Department for Education","false","2017-07-04","<p>The Department for Education is working jointly with the Department of Health on a children and young people’s mental health green paper, which we plan to publish by the end of the year.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-04T15:33:50.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731916/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731916/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731916/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Children: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, when her Department plans to publish its Green Paper on children's mental health.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731917","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>On 30 March, the Department published two consultation documents setting out proposals to improve statutory assessment in our primary schools.</p><p> </p><p>The first of these documents, ‘Primary assessment in England,’ set out wide ranging proposals designed to ensure that we have a settled, proportionate statutory assessment system that supports all pupils to fulfil their potential. The second document sought views on the recommendations made by the independent Rochford Review in relation to statutory assessment arrangements for pupils working below the standard of National Curriculum tests.</p><p> </p><p>Following a 12 week consultation period, we are now considering the responses we have received to those consultation documents and the Government response will be published in due course. We currently have no plans to carry out further formal public consultation exercises on primary assessment, although we will continue to listen to the views of stakeholders, and especially head teachers and teachers.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:27:11.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731917/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731917/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731917/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Primary Education: Assessments","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department plans to carry out further consultation on primary assessment in England.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","664"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731918","Department for Education","false","2017-07-04","<p>I refer to my answer to PQs 529 and 485.</p><p>Annual breakdowns of funding are not yet available.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-04T13:58:13.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731918/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731918/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731918/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much additional (a) revenue and (b) capital funding her Department plans to invest in further education colleges in (i) 2017-18, (ii) 2018-19, (iii) 2019-20, (iv) 2020-21 and (v) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","668"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731919","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government is reviewing its approach ‎to the financing of teacher training and its relationship to wider student support. We will announce our conclusions in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","472 ; 679","2017-06-29T16:29:23.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731919/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731919/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731919/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what estimate she has made of the cost to the public purse of debt forgiveness on student loan repayments for teachers in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731920","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government is reviewing its approach ‎to the financing of teacher training and its relationship to wider student support. We will announce our conclusions in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","472 ; 678","2017-06-29T16:29:23.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731920/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731920/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731920/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her Department's policy is on the level of debt forgiveness on student loan repayments for teachers.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731921","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>We will continue to work to ensure that every child has the opportunity to attend a good school and that all schools are fairly funded. We are considering the more than 25,000 responses we received to the National Funding Formula consultation, and will publish our response in due course. The cost of providing protections under the new funding formula will depend on the outcome of those considerations.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:28:46.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731921/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731921/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731921/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse will be of ensuring that no school will have its funding cut as part of the introduction of a new funding formula for schools in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","680"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731922","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>Since 2010 the schools budget has been protected in real terms. The pupil premium is currently worth £2.5 billion a year and this Government has committed to increase the school budget further, as well as continuing to protect the Pupil Premium to support those who need it. Further details on the cost of providing protections will be announced in due course.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:15:02.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731922/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731922/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731922/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Pupil Premium","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what the cost to the public purse will be of protecting the pupil premium in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731924","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>We have £170M of capital funding allocated to deliver new Institutes of Technology by 2021. A call for proposals will be launched later this year.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-07-03T14:30:15.067Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731924/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731924/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731924/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Institutes of Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much capital funding her Department plans to allocated to deliver new institutes of technology in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731925","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>Since launching the technical consultation on Analysing family circumstances and education on 12th April the close date has been extended to 31st July 2017 to allow more opportunity for responses. We will be discussing the method further with users and considering views on the methods set out here to consider the way forward for our analytical publications.</p><p> </p><p>We set out in the consultation document that we would welcome views on: expanding the number of years for analysis; including more sources of income; adjusting for housing costs; and on the methodology outlined for looking at ordinary working families, and how to refer to the group in DfE publications.</p><p> </p><p>Ahead of the original consultation being published, officials met with a range of academics working in the sector to discuss the proposed methodology and once we have collated responses received since the publication, will continue to seek further input from other interested groups. We will also continue to work closely with analysts at Department for Work and Pensions as we develop the data sources and methodology.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:25:20.717Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731925/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731925/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731925/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Children: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether her Department plans to carry out further consultation on analysing family circumstances and education.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731926","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Department for Transport continues to explore the practicability of implementing such a scheme or schemes, which is likely to include an analysis of the costs involved.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-06-29T12:00:23.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731926/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731926/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731926/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-22","Apprentices: Travel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the cost to the public purse of introducing discounted train and bus travel for apprentices in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","671"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731927","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Home Office annually publishes statistics on football-related arrests and banning orders connected with regulated international and domestic football matches involving English and Welsh clubs and the national teams.</p><p>The football-related arrests and banning orders, England and Wales: season 2015 to 2016 is the most recent publication on this area. The statistics stated in answer of 25 January 2017 to Question 60970 are the most up to date statistics the Home Office holds.</p><p>This publication can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/football-related-arrests-and-banning-orders-england-and-wales-season-2015-to-2016" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/football-related-arrests-and-banning-orders-england-and-wales-season-2015-to-2016</a></p><p>The Home Office intends to publish figures on football-related arrests and banning orders, England and Wales: season 2016 to 2017 later this year.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-26T15:45:01.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731927/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731927/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731927/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-22","Football: Racial Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, with reference to the Answer of 25 January 2017 to Question 60970, whether there have been more (a) racist incidents and (b) banning orders than those referred to for 1 July 2015 to 10 July 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","828"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731928","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer to Question UIN 486.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2017-06-30T13:52:25.143Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731928/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731928/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731928/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Further Education: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on attracting experienced industry professionals to work in further education colleges.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","801"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731929","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-06-30","<p>Our relationship with the European Union's agencies upon exit will be evaluated in light of delivering the twelve objectives outlined by the Prime Minister to achieve a deep and special partnership between the UK and the EU.</p><p> </p><p>No decisions have yet been made on our future relationship with the EU's agencies after leaving the EU. We are considering very carefully a range of options.</p><p> </p><p>As the Prime Minister has made clear the UK will continue to exercise its rights and fulfil its obligations as a member of the EU until our exit. This includes participation in the work of the Fundamental Rights Agency.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-06-30T13:23:02.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731929/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731929/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731929/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-06-22","European Union Agency for Fundamental Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the Government's policy is on UK engagement with the Fundamental Rights Agency after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","829"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731930","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>As part of our Industrial Strategy, we will launch a call for proposals to establish new Institutes of Technology later this year. The number of new institutions we approve will depend on the quality and number of bids we receive.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","567","2017-07-03T14:28:05.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731930/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731930/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731930/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Institutes of Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many new institutes of technology her Department plans to provide in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731931","Department for Education","false","2017-07-06","<p>Further detail on the manifesto commitment to look at the funding of further, technical and higher education will be provided in due course.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","488","2017-07-06T16:58:45.87Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731931/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731931/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731931/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Further Education: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if her Department will publish a Green Paper on funding for tertiary education.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731932","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Department is responsible for the management of the England European Regional Development Fund (ERDF) programme.</p><p>The Government announced in October 2016 that it will guarantee EU funding for European Structural and Investment (ESI) Funds projects that are signed before the UK's departure from the EU and which provide good value for money and support domestic priorities, even when these projects continue after we have left the EU. The England ERDF programme is covered by this guarantee.</p><p>As a result, British businesses and other organisations have additional certainty and can continue to apply for EU funding while the UK remains a member of the EU.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-06-29T17:35:11.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731932/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731932/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731932/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Local Government Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, which programmes his Department currently funds will have their funding affected by the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","830"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731933","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>Requests relating to any circumstances of paid or unpaid leave are a matter for teachers’ employers – in the case of maintained schools this would be for head teachers, based on policies agreed with the Local Authority. For academies, this would be for the head teacher to agree with the academy governing board.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-27T16:58:06.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731933/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731933/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731933/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on a new right to request (a) paid and (b) unpaid leave for training for teachers.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","804"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731934","Home Office","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government takes all hate crime seriously and published a Hate Crime Action Plan in July 2016 which sets out a comprehensive programme of work to drive forward action against hate crime.</p><p>We are currently assessing the impact of exiting the European Union on projects across Government, including any joint initiatives that we have with the European Union on hate crime.</p><p> </p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-06-29T16:20:56.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731934/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731934/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731934/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-22","Hate Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what assessment she has made of the potential implications for the funding of anti-hate crime projects of the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","831"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731935","Department for Education","false","2017-07-11","<p>In the 2017 Spring Budget, £5 million was allocated to increase the number of schemes in the public and private sector for people returning to work after time out of paid employment. The Government Equalities Office is leading on this, and proposals will be announced in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-07-11T16:41:14.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731935/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731935/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731935/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Teachers: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on a national retraining scheme for teachers.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","805"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731936","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>Key Stage 3 is a vital part of secondary education. The Government is clear that all pupils deserve to receive a broad and balanced curriculum in the first three years of secondary school.</p><p> </p><p>All secondary schools are held to account on the basis of their results at the end of Key Stage 4. Ofsted’s school inspection handbook makes clear that inspectors will consider the progress that pupils are making at the end of each year and each Key Stage.</p><p> </p><p>The Government is considering how best to improve accountability at Key Stage 3.</p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb","465","2017-06-29T15:58:12.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731936/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731936/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731936/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Secondary Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what her policy is on improving the accountability of schools at Key Stage 3.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","806"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731937","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-30","<p>Department of Culture, Media and Sport officials alongside officials from the Home Office, the Department for Communities and Local Government, Department for Education, the Ministry of Justice and criminal justice agencies are currently discussing the content and form of the Ministerial seminar.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-06-30T12:02:15.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731937/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731937/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731937/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-22","Internet: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions her Department has had with the Home Office on proposals for a ministerial seminar on hate on the internet.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731938","Home Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>The ministerial seminar on the internet referred to in Action Against Hate: The UK Government's plan for tackling hate crime, published in July 2016 will be held before the end of the year. Officials, from the Home Office, the Department for Communities and Local Government, the Department for Culture Media and Sports, Department for Education, the Ministry of Justice and criminal justice agencies are already consulting on the content and form of the proposed seminar.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-06-27T14:35:42.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731938/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731938/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731938/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-22","Hate Crime: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Government plans to convene the ministerial seminar on hate on the  internet referred to in Action Against Hate: The UK Government's plan for tackling hate crime, published in July 2016; and which Government departments will be consulted prior to that seminar on which victims' groups, stakeholders and industry representatives will be invited to attend.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731939","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-28","<p>We want UK fans to be able to enjoy a safe and secure visit to Russia for the World Cup next year. As part of the <em>Be on the Ball </em>campaign, the FCO has published specific travel advice for the World Cup (<a href="http://www.gov.uk/russia2018" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/russia2018</a>).</p><p>Regular meetings take place between UK officials and the Russian authorities to discuss preparations for major sporting events. For example, a UK delegation attended the Confederations Cup this month.</p><p>We also regularly raise our concerns with the Russian authorities on their human rights record.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-06-28T16:01:41.013Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731939/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731939/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731939/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-22","Russia: Discrimination","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Russian counterpart on plans to combat anti-Semitism, Islamophobia, racism, homophobia and other forms of discrimination at the 2018 World Cup in that country.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","834"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731940","Department for International Development","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Department for International Development currently employs 9 civil servants in the private offices of the two joint DFID and FCO ministers.</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-06-27T16:26:55.177Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731940/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731940/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731940/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-06-22","Department for International Development: Civil Servants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, how many civil servants of her Department will be employed to work in the private offices of the joint Department for International Development and Foreign and Commonwealth Office ministers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731941","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>The FCO employs 11 civil servants working in the private offices of the 2 joint DFID and FCO ministers. We will keep this under review and will make adjustments accordingly as the Ministers settle into their new roles.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-06-27T15:28:17.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731941/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731941/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731941/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-22","Department for International Development and Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Ministers' Private Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how many civil servants of his Department will be employed in the private offices of the joint Department for International Development and Foreign and Commonwealth Office ministers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731942","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>Ministers of State Stewart and Burt will build on the existing close cooperation between FCO and DFID to strengthen the coordination of Britain's diplomatic and development work around the world. Individual responsibilities for all FCO Ministers are available on our <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/foreign-commonwealth-office" target="_blank">website</a> (<a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/people/rory-stewart" target="_blank">Rory Stewart OBE MP</a> and <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/people/alistair-burt" target="_blank">Rt Hon Alistair Burt MP</a>).</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-06-27T15:19:39.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731942/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731942/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731942/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-22","Department for International Development and Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what the ministerial responsibilities are of the new joint Department for International Development and Foreign and Commonwealth Office ministers.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731943","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-06-27","<p>The number of soldiers and officers who have joined the Regular Army and Army Reserves in the last two financial years (FY), broken down by Regiment/Corps is shown in the attached tables.</p><p> </p><p>The figures are for total (trained and untrained) intake to the Regular Army and Army Future Reserves 2020 (FR20), excluding Gurkhas and Non-FR20 Reserve populations.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-06-27T16:07:08.037Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731943/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731943/answer","PQ06024.docx","855 - Recruited Army Regulars and Reserves","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731943/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-06-22","Armed Forces: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many soldiers and officers have been recruited to the (a) army and (b) reserve forces in the last two years, broken down by regiment.","false","Biography information for Stephen Doughty","Cardiff South and Penarth","Stephen Doughty","855"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731944","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>We received over 25,000 responses to the consultation, which we are analysing in detail. We are grateful to all those who expressed their views on school funding and the proposed formula as part of this process. We will publish the response to the consultation in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-27T12:49:40.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731944/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731944/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731944/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, from which school year the proposed national funding formula for schools will apply.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","865"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731945","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-27","<p>These proposals are part of a consultation; no final decisions have been made. We are currently consulting passengers for their views on future Southeastern train services. In the consultation we provided an example to demonstrate how a reduction of London termini could operate to deliver a more reliable service. As with any other consultation, if a large majority of consultees support or oppose one option over another, that will carry significant weight in deciding how to proceed, and in developing the specification for the next operator.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-27T14:01:00.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731945/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731945/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731945/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-22","Southeastern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will halt the proposals contained in the future of Southeastern Trains Franchise consultation to cut trains on the Bexleyheath line to Charing Cross and Victoria stations; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","846"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731946","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-28","<p>According to Sport England’s Active Places Power database which maps community sports facilities in England, 7 new eight-lane athletics tracks have been built in England since 2012. They are as follows;</p><p> </p><p>Edge Hill Sport in Ormskirk</p><p>Little Marlow Running Track in Marlow</p><p>Prissick Sports Village in Middlesbrough</p><p>Robert Blake and Elmwood Leisure in Bridgwater</p><p>St Marys School in Ascot</p><p>Victoria park in Warrington</p><p>Waltham Forest Feelgood Centre in Walthamstow</p><p> </p><p>This data can be found at: <a href="http://www.activeplacespower.com" target="_blank">www.activeplacespower.com</a></p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-06-28T09:47:41.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731946/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731946/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731946/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-22","Athletics: Sportsgrounds","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will list the locations of all eight-lane athletics tracks constructed in England since the 2012 Olympics.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731947","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>The previous Financial Secretary, in a letter to the hon. Member for Bassetlaw dated 19<sup>th</sup> April 2017, set out that a waiver of landfill tax for such cases would set a perverse incentive which may lead to the abandonment of other such waste sites. Therefore it would be counterproductive to waive the landfill tax liability in this case. I agree with this assessment.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has made no estimate as to the value of the site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has not held any meetings with other government departments concerning the removal of landfill tax from abandoned waste sites owned by the Crown Estate.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","259 ; 599","2017-06-27T15:13:19.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731947/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731947/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731947/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Landfill Tax: Crown Estate","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether HM Treasury officials have held meetings with other Government Departments in 2017 to discuss the removal of landfill tax from abandoned waste sites owned by the Crown Estate.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","877"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731948","Attorney General","false","2017-06-28","<p>Progress is being made on the Serious Fraud Office (SFO) investigation into allegations concerning GPT and aspects of the conduct of their business in the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia. However, as was the position in December 2016, it would not be appropriate for me to discuss the status of a live criminal investigation further at this stage.</p><p>When it is appropriate to do so the SFO publish updates on the status of the GPT case on their website. The most recent information can be found at: <a href="https://www.sfo.gov.uk/cases/gpt-special-project-management-ltd/" target="_blank">www.sfo.gov.uk/cases/gpt-special-project-management-ltd/</a>.</p><p> </p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-06-28T11:03:30.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731948/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731948/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731948/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-06-22","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, if he will provide an update on the status of the case of the hon. Member for Thirsk and Malton's constituent, as detailed in the letter of 14 December 2016 on the Serious Fraud Investigation into allegations concerning GPT and the conduct of its business in Saudi Arabia.","false","Biography information for Kevin Hollinrake","Thirsk and Malton","Kevin Hollinrake","554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731949","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-30","<p>We continue to keep permitted development rights, and the contribution they make to national housing delivery, under review.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-06-30T15:30:04.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731949/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731949/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731949/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Change of Use","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will review the suitability of commercial to residential conversions through permitted development.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731950","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-07-11","<p>Where work is necessary to ensure the fire safety of social housing, we will ensure that lack of financial resources will not prevent it going ahead.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-07-11T09:40:05.643Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731950/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731950/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731950/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","High Rise Flats: Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether additional resources will be made available to local authorities to help ensure the safety of tenants living in high-rise residential buildings.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731955","Department for Education","false","2017-07-03","<p>As part of our Industrial Strategy, we will launch a call for proposals to establish new Institutes of Technology later this year. The number of new institutions we approve will depend on the quality and number of bids we receive.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton","802","2017-07-03T14:28:06.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731955/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731955/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731955/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Institutes of Technology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many new institutes of technology her Department plans to provide in (a) 2017-18, (b) 2018-19, (c) 2019-20, (d) 2020-21 and (e) 2021-22.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731960","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>In the year to 2016, earnings for an average full-time employee grew in every UK region and nation. Earnings grew fastest in the West Midlands (+3.7%), followed by the North West (+3.0%) and Wales (+2.9%).</p><p> </p><p>In April this year we increased the National Living Wage by 4.2% to £7.50. The increase is expected to directly benefit around 1.7 million workers across the UK.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-06-27T09:38:34.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731960/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731960/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731960/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether the Government has made a recent assessment of wage growth across the regions.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731961","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Parliamentary Security Department works closely in partnership with the Metropolitan Police Service and will continue to ensure that appropriate resources, including from policing, are available to enable the safety and security of the Parliamentary Estate.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-06-28T09:29:48.673Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731961/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731961/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731961/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-06-22","House of Commons: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, if the Commission will undertake an impact assessment of the effect of changes in funding to frontline policing on public safety.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731962","Department for Education","false","2017-06-29","<p>We want to ensure every primary and secondary school has the resources it needs to deliver a high quality education for every pupil. That is why the core schools budget has been protected in real terms since 2010.</p><p> </p><p>Core school funding was at £39.6 billion in 2015-16 rising to £40.2 billion in 2016-17. It is set to rise from £41.0 billion in 2017-18 to £42.6 billion in 2019-20 with increasing pupil numbers.</p><p> </p><p>We know that how schools use their money is also important in delivering the best outcomes for pupils and we will continue to provide support to help them use their funding in cost effective ways. The Government has produced tools, information and guidance to support improved financial health and efficiency in schools, which can be found at: tinyurl.com/HUTWG36.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-29T16:05:24.293Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731962/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731962/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731962/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent estimate she has made of core school funding in each year from 2015 to 2019.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731963","Department for Education","false","2017-06-27","<p>The core schools budget has been protected in real terms since 2010 and is set to rise from £41 billion in 2017-18 to over £42 billion in 2019-20 with increasing pupil numbers. We are considering the more than 25,000 responses we received to the consultation on the National Funding Formula, and will publish our response in due course.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-06-27T13:19:41.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731963/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731963/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731963/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Schools: Harrow","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether she plans to increase funding for primary and secondary schools in Harrow in (a) 2018-19 and (b) 2019-20; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731964","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-27","<p>As the Northern Powerhouse Minister I am dedicated to ensuring the government continues to prioritise its plans for building a stronger northern economy.</p><p>In January we allocated over half a billion pounds of investment directly into the Northern Powerhouse for projects to boost local growth. And in February we launched the £400 million Northern Powerhouse Investment Fund to provide small-and-medium-sized businesses with the investment they need to start-up and grow.</p><p>The Government remains absolutely committed to the Northern Powerhouse—we are already seeing real, tangible progress and will continue to work with local partners and business across the North to get the job done.</p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2017-06-27T15:32:20.567Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731964/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731964/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731964/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what the Government's policy is on the future of the Northern Powerhouse.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731965","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-30","<p>The Government has no plans to issue guidance on limiting the number of UK registered bankers earning over one million euros.</p><p> </p><p>The UK is at the forefront of global efforts to tackle unacceptable pay practices in the banking sector and has the toughest regime on pay of any major financial centre.</p><p> </p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-06-30T11:31:32.527Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731965/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731965/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731965/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Banks: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to provide guidance on limiting the number of UK registered bankers earning over one million euros; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731966","Department for Education","false","2017-06-28","<p>The Department for Education is working alongside local partners including local authorities, schools, universities and businesses in 12 Opportunity Areas to develop and agree plans in due course. These plans, which will build on effective local initiatives to improve outcomes, will outline how we will ensure that children and young in each area can access high quality education and opportunities, at every stage of their life from early years to employment, and fulfil their potential.</p><p>We are taking an evidence-based approach that recognises the need to address long-standing challenges and barriers to social mobility, which will allow us to identify what works and spread this to other parts of the country that face similar challenges.</p><p>The work led by the Careers and Enterprise Company is one example of how we are increasing opportunity. We have committed to ensuring that young people between 11 and 18 benefit from high quality careers advice and at least four work placements through the course of their education. To deliver this commitment they have recruited Enterprise Advisers, to work with schools and colleges in all 12 areas and have the support of a number of a growing number of businesses.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-28T10:12:36.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731966/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731966/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731966/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-22","Education: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will provide an update on the Opportunity Areas programme.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731967","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-27","<p>At Budget 2016 the government announced cuts in business rates benefiting all ratepayers which are worth almost £9bn over the next 5 years. In addition, the government set out a £435 million package of measures to support those businesses most impacted by the recent revaluation. The government routinely meets stakeholders to discuss the business rates system and it will continue to do so.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-06-27T15:40:36.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731967/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731967/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731967/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether the Government plans to issue consultation exercise on changes to business rates.","true","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731968","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-29","<p>The Government currently has no plans to introduce restrictions on overseas ownership of new properties in London or elsewhere in the country, but will keep the issue under review.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-06-29T09:26:03.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731968/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731968/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731968/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731968/answer/previousversion/378","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Housing: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether he plans to introduce restrictions on the overseas ownership of new properties in London; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731969","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-29","<p>This Government recognises the important role housing co-operatives can play in delivering locally led and innovative housing.</p><p>The Community Housing Fund announced in December 2016 allocated £60 million to local authorities to support the community-led housing sector, including housing co-operatives. We have also encouraged community led groups, including housing co-operatives, to apply for funding from the £7.1 billion Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme 2016-21, which will deliver 225,000 affordable homes by March 2021.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-06-29T09:30:49.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731969/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731969/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731969/answer","Reading West","Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731969/answer/previousversion/382","Biography information for Alok Sharma","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-22","Housing: Cooperatives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, what his Department's policy is for the provision of additional co-operative housing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731970","Department for International Development","false","2017-06-27","<p>The UK has played a leading role in the Nepal earthquake response. Immediately after the 2015 earthquake, the Department for International Development (DFID) provided humanitarian relief for thousands of displaced people. This included reaching over 250,000 people with shelter support and providing over 200,000 people with clothes, blankets and mattresses.</p><p>We are now supporting reconstruction. We have already repaired water supplies for over 33,000 people, and rehabilitated 114km of remote trails. We are working with the Nepali Government to find solutions for all households who remain displaced by the earthquake. Over the next 5 years we will reach over 250,000 with improved water and sanitation and invest in housing reconstruction, supporting poorer households to rebuild safe homes.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-06-27T16:29:03.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731970/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731970/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731970/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-06-22","Nepal: Earthquakes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department has provided to earthquake recovery efforts in Nepal; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731971","Department for International Development","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Secretary of State visited Somalia on 17 June where she announced a further £60m uplift in UK support to drought relief operations, on top of a contribution of £110m announced last February. During her visit she said: “The UK stepped up early with support, and lobbied others to do more, which has prevented the spread of famine. We are showing our continued leadership with more food, more water and more medicine for those at imminent risk of dying from drought and conflict. The world must follow our lead and act now to put an end to humanitarian crises that threaten our global stability and help accelerate progress on peace, security and prosperity – which is firmly in everyone’s interest.”</p><p> </p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-06-27T16:28:00.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731971/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731971/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731971/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-06-22","Somalia: Famine","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what support her Department is providing to famine relief operations in Somalia; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731972","Home Office","false","2017-06-27","<p>It is the responsibility of individual fire and rescue authorities to assess and plan for potential risks at sites in their local area, as part of the process of the Integrated Risk Management Plan (IRMP) for their area. The scale and costs of meeting these needs is therefore a matter for the local fire and rescue service.</p><p>The Chief Fire Officers Association have worked closely with Waste Industry Safety and Health (WISH), and Environment Agency, to provide industry advice on minimising fire risk.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2017-06-27T10:24:51.03Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731972/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731972/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731972/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-22","Waste Disposal: Worksop","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate she has made of the potential cost to the fire service in the event of a major fire at the waste site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731973","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-28","<p>Location by location assessments of all possible line closures are generally not conducted as they would require a significant number of variables and assumptions. An estimate in this specific instance has therefore not been made. The industry focuses on developing robust contingency planning processes to minimise the impact to the customer in the event of a disruption.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-28T14:40:21.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731973/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731973/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731973/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-22","Northern: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate he has made of the potential costs of closure of the Northern rail line from Sheffield to Worksop in the event of a fire at the abandoned waste recycling site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731974","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-27","<p>The previous Financial Secretary, in a letter to the hon. Member for Bassetlaw dated 19<sup>th</sup> April 2017, set out that a waiver of landfill tax for such cases would set a perverse incentive which may lead to the abandonment of other such waste sites. Therefore it would be counterproductive to waive the landfill tax liability in this case. I agree with this assessment.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has made no estimate as to the value of the site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury has not held any meetings with other government departments concerning the removal of landfill tax from abandoned waste sites owned by the Crown Estate.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","259 ; 877","2017-06-27T15:13:19.55Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731974/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731974/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731974/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-22","Waste Disposal: Worksop","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate he has made of the value of the waste site at Sandy Lane, Worksop.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731975","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-06-30","<p>The site at Sandy lane was abandoned in October 2016 and from this point onwards there has been no site management. There have however been regular Police and Fire service patrols and the site is monitored using CCTV.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency is working with Local Resilience Forum members, including Bassetlaw District Council, the Nottinghamshire Fire Service, Nottinghamshire County Council and Public Health England, to manage the risks at the site and is acting to clear the waste that also poses a risk to human health.</p><p> </p><p>There are three main waste streams which have been left at the site: mixed non-hazardous combustible waste in and around the transfer building; mixed construction and demolition (C&amp;D) non-combustible waste outside and the bags of polyurethane foam, mostly deposited in the centre of the site. The table below outlines the estimated costs associated with each waste stream. The cost of this clearance, excluding landfill tax have not been included as the landfill tax is not waived, which has been previously communicated by HMT to the HM for Bassetlaw.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Waste</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Estimated quantity (tonnes)</strong><strong><sup>1</sup></strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Estimated Costs in £k (including Landfill Tax)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Mixed C&amp;D non-combustible</p></td><td><p>20,000</p></td><td><p>3,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Non-Hazardous combustible</p></td><td><p>2,500</p></td><td><p>375</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Polyurethane foam</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>20</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><sup>1</sup>The tonnages have been estimated by officers’ observations on site. A more accurate assessment of the volumes of waste present at the site would cost around £5K.</p><p> </p><p>The main environmental and health risk from the site is from the polyurethane foam left on site. The Environment Agency, county and district councils have set funds aside and are making plans to remove this foam as soon as possible.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency has also been working in close partnership with Bassetlaw District Council, Notts Fire &amp; Rescue Service, Police, the County Council and Public Health England, to create a tactical plan which will be implemented in the event of a fire. The Notts Fire &amp; Rescue Service will shortly be entering the site and will attempt to move wastes around the site to allow for fire breaks and better access.</p><p> </p><p>The other environmental risks are in relation to the degradation of the waste. The Environment Agency, Fire and Rescue Service and Bassetlaw DC do have powers to intervene in exceptional circumstances where there is a serious risk to the environment and health.</p><p> </p><p>The Environment Agency is continuing its investigation into the former operators of the site. There is close contact about the site at official level across Government agencies. The Secretary of State has not discussed the site with Cabinet colleagues since his appointment on 11 June.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey","419 ; 601 ; 602","2017-06-30T11:35:48.43Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731975/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731975/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731975/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-06-22","Waste Disposal: Worksop","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate he has made of the cost of clearing waste from the waste site at Sandy Lane, Worksop (a) including and (b) not including landfill tax forgone.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","600"
