"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731294","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-26","<p>I believe that it is essential that consumers get a fair deal and that falls in oil prices are passed on to lower retail prices. A competitive market is the best way to keep prices low.</p><p> </p><p>Fuel pricing is subject to UK competition law under the Competition and Markets Authority, and we do not believe that an independent body to regulate fuel pricing is necessary.</p><p> </p><p>The Department closely monitors average retail petrol and diesel prices and publishes these data regularly. <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/oil-and-petroleum-products-weekly-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/oil-and-petroleum-products-weekly-statistics</a>.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Watford","Richard Harrington",,"2017-06-26T13:28:42.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731294/answer","Biography information for Richard Harrington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731294/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731294/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Fuels: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will bring forward legislative proposals to establish a regulatory body for fuel pricing.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","64"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731295","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-06-27","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring economic security for people at every stage of their life, including when they reach retirement. The Government is also clear that fairness between the generations must be maintained. We are committed to the Triple Lock for the remainder of this Parliament.</p>","Hexham","Guy Opperman",,"2017-06-27T10:03:32.927Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731295/answer","Biography information for Guy Opperman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731295/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731295/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-06-21","State Retirement Pensions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of ending the triple lock on pensions on pensioner poverty.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","65"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731296","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>On 3 March 2017, my department published its <em>Early Years Workforce Strategy</em>, setting out actions to support the development of a well-qualified workforce with the appropriate knowledge, skills and experience to deliver high quality early education and childcare for children from birth to age five.</p><p> </p><p>The Early Years Workforce Strategy can be viewed online:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-workforce-strategy" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/early-years-workforce-strategy</a></p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-06-30T13:23:56.01Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731296/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731296/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731296/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Pre-school Education: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps the Government is taking to recruit a specialist, highly-trained early years workforce.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","75"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731297","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-06-26","<p>The changes made to the existing third party campaigning rules by the Transparency of Lobbying Act 2014 do not restrict charities’ freedom to campaign to further their charitable purposes in a non-partisan way, but instead make the political system more accountable. At the 2015 general election, 68 organisations were registered with the Electoral Commission as third party campaigners undertaking campaigning activity which could influence the election outcome, of which 11 were charities.</p>","Chatham and Aylesford","Tracey Crouch",,"2017-06-26T16:22:50.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731297/answer","Biography information for Tracey Crouch","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731297/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731297/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2017-06-21","Charities: Lobbying","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, if she will make an assessment of the effect of the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014 on the work of charities.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","76"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731298","Cabinet Office","true","2017-06-27","<p><del class="ministerial">One organisation has been fined for failing to comply with regulations on third party campaigning set out in the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014. The Electoral Commission announced on 19 April 2017 that it had imposed a civil monetary penalty on Greenpeace Ltd, as the organisation did not register with the Electoral Commission at the 2015 General Election. Greenpeace Ltd was fined a total of £30,000.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">The rules on third party campaigning at elections are set out in the Political Parties Elections and Referendums Act 2000. These rules were amended by the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014.</ins></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Since the amendments made by the 2014 Act came into force, three organisations have been fined by the Electoral Commission. On 19 April 2016, the Electoral Commission announced that it had fined Steve Hart from the Centre for Labour and Social Studies £1100 for failing to deliver two donations reports on time. On 19 April 2017, the Commission announced that it had fined Greenpeace Limited a total of £30,000 and Friends of the Earth Limited £1000. Both organisations did not register with the Electoral Commission at the 2015 UK Parliamentary General Election before spending in excess of the registration threshold.</ins></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-06-27T14:55:37.523Z","2017-08-03T11:02:42.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731298/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731298/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731298/answer","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731298/answer/previousversion/304","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-06-21","Lobbying: Fines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many organisations have been fined for failing to comply with regulations on third party campaigning set out in the Transparency of Lobbying, Non-party Campaigning and Trade Union Administration Act 2014.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","77"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731299","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Department published the interim findings of our JSA Early Warning Sanctions Trial in December 2016 and we expect the full evaluation later this summer. We will consider the findings from both reports before making decisions on any future roll-out.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2017-06-26T13:10:19.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731299/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731299/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731299/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-06-21","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to decide on the extension of the yellow card early warning system for benefit sanctions across the UK","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","85"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731300","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-26","<p>Government has undertaken a significant amount of work to assess the economic impacts of leaving the EU. This is part of our continued programme of rigorous and extensive analytical work on a range of scenarios on a sector by sector basis.</p><p> </p><p>All departments need to prepare not just for a negotiated settlement, but also for the no deal scenario. We are confident that we will secure a good deal for the UK, but are prepared should there be no deal.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2017-06-26T15:17:23.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731300/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731300/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731300/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Productivity","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the potential effect on the level of UK GDP of the UK leaving the EU prior to the conclusion of any deal with the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731301","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Department undertakes regular resource reviews to ensure that we are appropriately resourced to deal with the task at hand. We will ensure we have the right skills to get the best deal for the UK. The Department is recruiting the brightest and the best from across the civil service, the wider public sector and the private sector. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has over 450 staff, and is growing fast.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-06-26T13:32:33.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731301/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731301/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731301/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-06-21","Department for Exiting the European Union: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what estimate his Department has made of the number of officials it has yet to recruit which it requires for the negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731302","Department for International Trade","false","2017-06-26","<p>As the Prime Minister has said, we want to build a truly Global Britain that is one of the firmest advocates for free trade anywhere in the world. We cannot initiate or conclude negotiations on trade agreements while we remain a member of the EU. We are considering our future trading relationships with all our partners as we prepare to leave the EU. Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","156 ; 157","2017-06-26T14:21:05.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731302/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731302/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731302/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-21","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the timetable is for trade negotiations formally to commence with non-EU countries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","155"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731303","Department for International Trade","false","2017-06-26","<p>As the Prime Minister has said, we want to build a truly Global Britain that is one of the firmest advocates for free trade anywhere in the world. We cannot initiate or conclude negotiations on trade agreements while we remain a member of the EU. We are considering our future trading relationships with all our partners as we prepare to leave the EU. Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","155 ; 157","2017-06-26T14:21:05.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731303/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731303/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731303/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-21","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what estimate his Department has made of the number of trade agreements it will plan to commence with non-EU countries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","156"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731304","Department for International Trade","false","2017-06-26","<p>As the Prime Minister has said, we want to build a truly Global Britain that is one of the firmest advocates for free trade anywhere in the world. We cannot initiate or conclude negotiations on trade agreements while we remain a member of the EU. We are considering our future trading relationships with all our partners as we prepare to leave the EU. Ministers and officials in the Department for International Trade are working closely with counterparts across a wide range of markets in order to promote the UK as a great place to do business and with which to trade.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","155 ; 156","2017-06-26T14:21:05.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731304/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731304/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731304/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-06-21","Trade Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the timetable is for concluding trade negotiations with non-EU countries.","false","Biography information for Jim Shannon","Strangford","Jim Shannon","157"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731305","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union has released information on the composition of the UK's senior negotiating team which is publicly available on <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/620076/Biographies_of_the_Civil_Service_representatives_for_the_negotiations_with_the_EU_.pdf" target="_blank">GOV.UK</a>. The senior civil servants, at grades SCS2 and above, who took part in the first round of the negotiations on 19 June 2017 are set out below. DExEU is drawing together expertise from a wide range of departments where there is specific relevant knowledge.</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>Oliver Robbins, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Sir Tim Barrow, UKRep</p></li><li><p>Glyn Williams, Home Office</p></li><li><p>Alex Ellis, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Mark Bowman, HMT</p></li><li><p>Simon Case, UKRep</p></li><li><p>Jonathan Black, HMT</p></li><li><p>Chris Jones, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Catherine Webb, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Catherine Adams, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Daniel Denman, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Matt Baugh, DExEU</p></li><li><p>Ian Walsh, DWP</p></li></ul><p> </p>","Wycombe","Mr Steve Baker",,"2017-06-26T16:37:16.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731305/answer","Biography information for Mr Steve Baker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731305/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731305/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-06-21","Department for Exiting the European Union: Females","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what proportion of his senior negotiating team are women.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","160"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731306","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>​On 17 February, the Foreign Secretary, discussed Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's case with the Iranian Foreign Minister. Mrs Zaghari-Ratcliffe's family in Tehran have confirmed she has legal representation. The Iranian position on dual nationality makes progress difficult and we do not interfere with the legal systems of other countries. Nonetheless we will continue to raise her case with the Iranian authorities at the highest levels at every available opportunity, as I did in a telephone call with the Iranian Deputy Foreign Minister on 21 June.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2017-06-26T12:59:40.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731306/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731306/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731306/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-06-21","Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what representations he has made to his counterpart in Iran on the decision of the Supreme Court in Iran not to free British-Iranian Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe; what steps he has taken to make sure Nazanin Zaghari-Ratcliffe can see her lawyer; and what steps plans to take to ensure she is free.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","161"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731307","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Government was clear in its White Paper that we aim to have as seamless and frictionless a border as possible between Northern Ireland and Ireland. There is a very strong commitment from the UK and Irish Governments to find a practical solution that recognises the unique circumstances on the land border between Northern Ireland and Ireland. We welcome the European Council’s commitment to develop flexible and imaginative solutions, and the establishment of a dialogue between the UK and EU Commission to discuss this issue.</p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2017-06-26T13:50:14.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731307/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731307/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731307/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-06-21","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the effect of withdrawing from the single market on the land border between Northern Ireland and the Republic of Ireland.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","162"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731308","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-06-29","<p>Science and research are vital to our country’s prosperity, security and wellbeing. This Government wants the UK to be the go-to place for innovators and investors across the world, and we intend to secure the best possible outcome for the UK research base as we exit the European Union.</p><p> </p><p>We would welcome an agreement to continue to collaborate with our European partners on major science, research, and technology initiatives. We will be approaching the negotiations on this basis. However it is too early to speculate on the UK’s future relationship with specific EU research programmes, including Horizon 2020 and successor programmes. Whatever happens in the future, the Government is committed to ensuring the UK remains a world leader in international research and innovation, including research into musculoskeletal conditions.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2017-06-29T14:38:26.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731308/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731308/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731308/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2017-06-21","Musculoskeletal Disorders: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if he will take steps to ensure continued UK participation in EU research programmes into musculoskeletal conditions after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Martyn Day","Linlithgow and East Falkirk","Martyn Day","185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731309","Prime Minister","false","2017-06-30","<p>As has been the practice under successive Governments, information relating to the proceedings of Cabinet Committees is not disclosed.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-06-30T11:59:19.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731309/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731309/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731309/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-06-21","EU Exit and Trade Committee","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, on how many occasions the EU Exit and Trade Cabinet Committee has met; and who chaired each such meeting.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731310","Department for Transport","false","2017-06-26","<p>The Chris Gibb report was published by the Department for Transport on 22 June 2017. The report is now available on the GOV.UK website along with the Secretary of State’s response.</p><p> </p><p>Please see links provided:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/southern-rail-network-gibb-report" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/southern-rail-network-gibb-report</a></p><p>SoS response link: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/news/gibb-report-on-southern-rail-network-government-response" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/news/gibb-report-on-southern-rail-network-government-response</a></p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-06-26T14:58:04.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731310/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731310/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731310/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-06-21","Southern: Standards","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he plans to publish the report by Chris Gibb on the Southern rail franchise and the Government's response to that report.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731311","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-29","<p>There are no specific estimates of concealed income from image rights payments. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) undertakes compliance activity to ensure that football clubs, players and managers pay the correct amount of tax. Since 2014-15 HMRC has brought in over £260m from tackling non-compliance in the football industry. HMRC is currently investigating 67 footballers, 39 football clubs and 13 agents for a range of issues including image rights abuse.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-06-29T13:47:01.277Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731311/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731311/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731311/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Taxation: Football","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will estimate the amount of revenue lost to the Exchequer as a result of professional football players and managers concealing income from image rights; and what steps he is taking to prevent that practice.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","187"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731312","Home Office","false","2017-06-26","<p>The review into the funding of Islamist extremism in the UK was commissioned by the former Prime Minister and reported to the Home Secretary and the Prime Minister in 2016. The review has improved the Government’s understanding of the nature, scale and sources of funding for Islamist extremism in the UK. Publication of the review is a decision for the Prime Minister.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-06-26T13:29:31.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731312/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731312/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731312/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-06-21","Radicalism","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will place in the Library a copy of her Department's report on foreign funding of extremism and radicalisation in the UK.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731313","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-30","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) checks that employers and employees are tax compliant by undertaking targeted compliance activity. In the temporary labour market, it has challenged non-compliant businesses with the effect that those businesses have changed their business model. HMRC continues to challenge umbrella companies who do not comply with their obligations.</p><p>There has been no recent assessment made on the effect of the growth of umbrella companies on tax revenues. The government does not have a record of the number of people registered to work specifically through umbrella companies.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","189 ; 58","2017-06-30T10:54:56.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731313/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731313/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731313/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he had made of the effect of the growth of umbrella companies on tax revenues.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","188"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731314","HM Treasury","false","2017-06-30","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) checks that employers and employees are tax compliant by undertaking targeted compliance activity. In the temporary labour market, it has challenged non-compliant businesses with the effect that those businesses have changed their business model. HMRC continues to challenge umbrella companies who do not comply with their obligations.</p><p>There has been no recent assessment made on the effect of the growth of umbrella companies on tax revenues. The government does not have a record of the number of people registered to work specifically through umbrella companies.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","188 ; 58","2017-06-30T10:54:56.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731314/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731314/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731314/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-06-21","Tax Avoidance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether he plans to review the use of umbrella companies by employers and employment agencies.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","189"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731315","Department for Education","false","2017-06-30","<p>I am sorry, but data on these matters are not collected centrally by the Department for Education. Each local authority maintains its own records of such interventions.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill","282","2017-06-30T08:11:32.23Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731315/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731315/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731315/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-06-21","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many interventions under section 437(1) of the Education Act 1996, for home schooling, have been made by local authorities in the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mrs Sharon Hodgson","Washington and Sunderland West","Mrs Sharon Hodgson","213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731316","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-06-30","<p>We continue to keep permitted development rights, and the contribution they make to national housing delivery, under review.</p><p>The Department publishes data on permitted development rights[1] and the number of homes delivered under the rights for each local authority[2]. Separate data is also published on planning decisions for the change of use by local authority area.[3]</p><p> </p><p><em>[1] Table PDR 1: District planning authorities - applications for prior approvals for permitted developments, by local planning authority <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-planning-application-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-planning-application-statistics</a></em></p><p><em>[2] Table 123 Housing Supply; net additional dwellings, component flows of, by local authority district, England: 2012-13 to 2015-16 </em><em><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-net-supply-of-housing" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-net-supply-of-housing</a></em></p><p><em>[3] Table 124A District planning authorities- planning decisions by development type and local planning authority (yearly) <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-planning-application-statistics" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/live-tables-on-planning-application-statistics</a></em></p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2017-06-30T15:34:17.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731316/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731316/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731316/answer","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/731316/answer/previousversion/605","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-06-21","Change of Use","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will review the rules governing permitted development for change of use from commercial and industrial to residential; and what estimate he has made of changes in use by borough in each year from 2010 to 2015.","false","Biography information for Sir Vince Cable","Twickenham","Sir Vince Cable","242"
